# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: svg-graphics
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:svg-graphics/element-path] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:svg-graphics/element-path] It’s been available across browsers since July 2015.
[src:svg-graphics/element-path] The **`<path>`** SVG element is the generic element to define a shape.
[src:svg-graphics/element-path] All the basic shapes can be created with a path element.
[src:svg-graphics/element-path] This attribute defines the shape of the path.
[src:svg-graphics/element-path] This attribute lets authors specify the total length for the path, in user units.
[src:svg-graphics/element-path] This element implements the `SVGPathElement` interface.
[src:svg-graphics/element-rect] The **`<rect>`** SVG element is a basic SVG shape that draws rectangles, defined by their position, width, and height.
[src:svg-graphics/element-rect] The rectangles may have their corners rounded.
[src:svg-graphics/element-rect] The horizontal corner radius of the rect.
[src:svg-graphics/element-rect] The total length of the rectangle's perimeter, in user units.
[src:svg-graphics/element-rect] This element implements the `SVGRectElement` interface.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] SVG images are defined in a vector graphics format and stored in XML text files.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] SVG images can thus be scaled in size without loss of quality, and SVG files can be searched, indexed, scripted, and compressed.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] The XML text files can be created and edited with text editors or vector graphics editors, and are rendered by most web browsers.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] SVG can include JavaScript, potentially leading to cross-site scripting.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] SVG has been in development within the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C) since 1999 after six competing proposals for vector graphics languages had been submitted to the consortium during 1998 (see below).
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] The early SVG Working Group decided not to develop any of the commercial submissions, but to create a new markup language that was informed by but not really based on any of them.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] The working group was chaired at the time by Chris Lilley of the W3C.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] Early adoption was limited due to lack of support in older versions of Internet Explorer.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] However, as of 2011, all major desktop browsers began to support SVG.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] Native browser support offers various advantages, such as not requiring plugins, allowing SVG to be mixed with other content, and improving rendering and scripting reliability.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] Mobile support for SVG exists in various forms, with different devices and browsers supporting SVG Tiny 1.1 or 1.2.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] SVG can be produced using vector graphics editors and rendered into raster formats.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] In web-based applications, Inline SVG allows embedding SVG content within HTML documents.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] The SVG specification was updated to version 1.1 in 2011.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] Scalable Vector Graphics 2 became a W3C Candidate Recommendation on 15 September 2016.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] SVG 2 incorporates several new features in addition to those of SVG 1.1 and SVG Tiny 1.2.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] SVG 2 reached the Candidate Recommendation stage on 15 September 2016, and revised versions were published on 7 August 2018 and 4 October 2018.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] The latest draft was released on 14 September 2025.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] SVG supports interactivity, animation, and rich graphical capabilities, making it suitable for both web and print applications.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] SVG images can be compressed with the gzip algorithm, resulting in SVGZ files that are typically 20–50% smaller than the original.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] SVG also supports metadata, enabling better indexing, searching, and retrieval of SVG content.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] SVG allows three types of graphic objects: vector graphic shapes (such as paths consisting of straight lines and curves), bitmap images, and text.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] Graphical objects can be grouped, styled, transformed and composited into previously rendered objects.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] The feature set includes nested transformations, clipping paths, alpha masks, filter effects and template objects.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] SVG drawings can be interactive and can include animation, defined in the SVG XML elements or via scripting that accesses the SVG Document Object Model (DOM).
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] SVG uses CSS for styling and JavaScript for scripting.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] Text, including internationalization and localization, appearing in plain text within the SVG DOM, enhances the accessibility of SVG graphics.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] Though the SVG Specification primarily focuses on vector graphics markup language, its design includes the basic capabilities of a page description language like Adobe's PDF.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] It contains provisions for rich graphics, and is compatible with CSS for styling purposes.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] SVG has the information needed to place each glyph and image in a chosen location on a printed page.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] SVG drawings can be dynamic and interactive.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] Time-based modifications to the elements can be described in SMIL, or can be programmed in a scripting language (e.g.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] The W3C explicitly recommends SMIL as the standard for animation in SVG.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] A rich set of event handlers such as "onmouseover" and "onclick" can be assigned to any SVG graphical object to apply actions and events.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] Because of industry demand, two mobile profiles were introduced with SVG 1.1: *SVG Tiny* (SVGT) and *SVG Basic* (SVGB).
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] These are subsets of the full SVG standard, mainly intended for user agents with limited capabilities.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] In particular, SVG Tiny was defined for highly restricted mobile devices such as cellphones; it does not support styling or scripting.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] SVG Basic was defined for higher-level mobile devices, such as smartphones.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] In 2003, the 3GPP, an international telecommunications standards group, adopted SVG Tiny as the mandatory vector graphics media format for next-generation phones.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] SVGT is the required vector graphics format and support of SVGB is optional for Multimedia Messaging Service (MMS) and Packet-switched Streaming Service.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] It was later added as required format for vector graphics in 3GPP IP Multimedia Subsystem (IMS).
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] Neither mobile profile includes support for the full Document Object Model (DOM), while only SVG Basic has optional support for scripting, but because they are fully compatible subsets of the full standard, most SVG graphics can still be rendered by devices which only support the mobile profiles.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] SVGT 1.2 adds a microDOM (μDOM), styling and scripting.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] SVGT 1.2 also includes some features not found in SVG 1.1, including non-scaling strokes, which are supported by some SVG 1.1 implementations, such as Opera, Firefox, and WebKit.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] As shared code bases between desktop and mobile browsers increased, the use of SVG 1.1 over SVGT 1.2 also increased.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] SVG images, being XML, contain many repeated fragments of text, so they are well suited for lossless data compression algorithms.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] When an SVG image has been compressed with the gzip algorithm, it is referred to as an "SVGZ" image and uses the corresponding `.svgz` filename extension.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] Conforming SVG 1.1 viewers will display compressed images.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] An SVGZ file is typically 20 to 50 percent of the original size.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] W3C provides SVGZ files to test for conformance.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] (for "line to") precedes a point to which a line should be drawn.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] In all cases, absolute coordinates follow capital letter commands and relative coordinates are used after the equivalent lower-case letters.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] Straight-line paths and paths made up of a series of connected straight-line segments (polylines), as well as closed polygons, circles, and ellipses can be drawn.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] Rectangles and round-cornered rectangles are also standard elements.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] SVG shapes can be filled and outlined (painted with a color, a gradient, or a pattern).
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] Fills may be opaque, or have any degree of transparency.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] "Markers" are line-end features, such as arrowheads, or symbols that can appear at the vertices of a polygon.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] SVG shapes can be filled or outlined with solid colors as above, or with color gradients or with repeating patterns.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] Color gradients can be linear or radial (circular), and can involve any number of colors as well as repeats.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] Opacity gradients can also be specified.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] Gradients and patterns can be animated and scripted.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] could usefully be added to the SVG specification.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] The current draft of SVG 2 includes gradient meshes.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] regions that can be painted (with colors, gradients and patterns) independently.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] SVG images can interact with users in many ways.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] , mouse clicks, scrolling or zooming the image and other pointer, keyboard and document events.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] Event handlers may start, stop or alter animations as well as trigger scripts in response to such events.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] can link to SVG files that change the visible area of the document.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] This allows for creating specific view states that are used to zoom in/out of a specific area or to limit the view to a specific element.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] element also allow linking to and re-using internal and external elements.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] This allows coders to do more with less markup and makes for cleaner code.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] All aspects of an SVG document can be accessed and manipulated using scripts in a similar way to HTML.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] (DOM) objects for every SVG element and attribute.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] They can run in response to pointer events, keyboard events and document events as required.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] Content can be animated by manipulating the DOM using ECMAScript and the scripting language's built-in timers.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] Animations can be continuous, they can loop and repeat, and they can respond to user events, as mentioned above.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] As with HTML and CSS, text in SVG may reference external font files, such as system fonts.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] If the required font files do not exist on the machine where the SVG file is rendered, the text may not appear as intended.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] metadata properties (e.g. title, creator/author, subject, description, etc.).
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] Other metadata schemas may also be used.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] elements where authors may also provide plain-text descriptive material within an SVG image to help indexing, searching and retrieval by a number of means.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] An SVG document can define components including shapes, gradients etc., and use them repeatedly.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] SVG images can also contain raster graphics, such as PNG and JPEG images, and further SVG images.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] The use of SVG on the web was limited by the lack of support in older versions of Internet Explorer (IE).
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] Many websites that serve SVG images also provide the images in a raster format, either automatically by HTTP content negotiation or by allowing the user directly to choose the file.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] Konqueror was the first browser to support SVG in release version 3.2 in February 2004.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] As of 2011, all major desktop browsers, and many minor ones, have some level of SVG support.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] Other browsers' implementations are not yet complete; see comparison of layout engines for further details.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] However, SVG images may be included in XHTML pages using XML namespaces.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] Tim Berners-Lee, the inventor of the World Wide Web, was critical of early versions of Internet Explorer for its failure to support SVG.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] There are several advantages to native and full support: plugins are not needed, SVG can be freely mixed with other content in a single document, and rendering and scripting become considerably more reliable.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] Support for SVG may be limited to SVGT on older or more limited smart phones or may be primarily limited by their respective operating system.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] Adobe Flash Lite has optionally supported SVG Tiny since version 1.1.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] At the SVG Open 2005 conference, Sun demonstrated a mobile implementation of SVG Tiny 1.1 for the Connected Limited Device Configuration (CLDC) platform.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] Mobiles that use Opera Mobile, as well as the iPhone's built in browser, also include SVG support.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] However, even though it used the WebKit engine, the Android built-in browser did not support SVG prior to v3.0 (Honeycomb).
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] Prior to v3.0, Firefox Mobile 4.0b2 (beta) for Android was the first browser running under Android to support SVG by default.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] The level of SVG Tiny support available varies from mobile to mobile, depending on the SVG engine installed.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] Many newer mobile products support additional features beyond SVG Tiny 1.1, like gradient and opacity; this is sometimes referred to as "SVGT 1.1+", though there is no such standard.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] RIM's BlackBerry has built-in support for SVG Tiny 1.1 since version 5.0.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] Support continues for WebKit-based BlackBerry Torch browser in OS 6 and 7.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] Nokia's S60 platform has built-in support for SVG.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] For example, icons are generally rendered using the platform's SVG engine.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] Nokia has also led the JSR 226: Scalable 2D Vector Graphics API expert group that defines Java ME API for SVG presentation and manipulation.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] This API has been implemented in S60 Platform 3rd Edition Feature Pack 1 and onward.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] Some Series 40 phones also support SVG (such as Nokia 6280).
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] Most Sony Ericsson phones beginning with K700 (by release date) support SVG Tiny 1.1.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] Phones beginning with K750 also support such features as opacity and gradients.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] Phones with Sony Ericsson Java Platform-8 have support for JSR 226.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] Windows Phone has supported SVG since version 7.5.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] SVG is also supported on various mobile devices from Motorola, Samsung, LG, and Siemens mobile/BenQ-Siemens. eSVG, an SVG rendering library mainly written for embedded devices, is available on some mobile platforms.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] SVG images can be hand-coded or produced by the use of a vector graphics editor, such as Inkscape, Adobe Illustrator, Adobe Animate, or CorelDRAW, and rendered to common raster image formats such as PNG using the same software.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] Additionally, editors like Inkscape and Boxy SVG provide tools to trace raster images to Bézier curves typically using image tracing back-ends like potrace, autotrace, and imagetracerjs.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] Software can be programmed to render SVG images by using a library such as librsvg used by GNOME since 2000, Batik and ThorVG since 2020 for lightweight systems.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] SVG images can also be rendered to any desired popular image format by using ImageMagick, a free command-line utility (which also uses librsvg under the hood).
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] For web-based applications, the mode of usage termed Inline SVG allows SVG content to be embedded within an HTML document using an `<svg>` tag.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] Its graphical capabilities can then be employed to create sophisticated user interfaces as the SVG and HTML share context, event handling, and CSS.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] Other uses for SVG include embedding for use in word processing (e.g. with LibreOffice) and desktop publishing (e.g.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] Scribus), plotting graphs (e.g. gnuplot), and importing paths (e.g. for use in GIMP or Blender).
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] The application services Microsoft 365 and Microsoft Office 2019 offer support for exporting, importing and editing SVG images.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] The Uniform Type Identifier for SVG used by Apple is `public.svg-image` and conforms to `public.image` and `public.xml`.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] As a document format, similar to HTML documents, SVG can host scripts or CSS.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] This is an issue when an attacker can upload a SVG file, such as a profile picture, to a website and the file is treated as a normal picture, but contains malicious content.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] For instance, if an SVG file is deployed as a CSS background image, or a logo on some website, or in some image gallery, then, when the image is loaded in a browser, it activates a script or other content.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] This could lock up the browser (the Billion laughs attack), but could also lead to HTML injection and cross-site scripting attacks.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] The W3C therefore stipulates certain requirements when SVG is simply used for images: SVG Security.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] The W3C says that Inline SVG (an SVG file loaded natively on a website) is considered less of a security risk because the content is part of a greater document, and so scripting and CSS would not be unexpected.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] The MPEG-4 Part 20 standard – *Lightweight Application Scene Representation (LASeR) and Simple Aggregation Format (SAF)* is based on SVG Tiny.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] It was developed by MPEG (ISO/IEC JTC 1/SC29/WG11) and published as ISO/IEC 14496-20:2006.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] SVG capabilities are enhanced in MPEG-4 Part 20 with key features for mobile services, such as dynamic updates, binary encoding, state-of-art font representation.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] SVG was also accommodated in MPEG-4 Part 11, in the Extensible MPEG-4 Textual (XMT) format – a textual representation of the MPEG-4 multimedia content using XML.
[src:svg-graphics/scalable-vector-graphics] While SVG has received widespread adoption in the market as the de-facto standard for scalable vector graphics, the files are still not natively supported in Windows, so users must download an SVG preview thumbnailer for the File Explorer or use an alternate file explorer with native support.
[src:svg-graphics/vector-graphics] While vector hardware has largely disappeared in favor of raster-based monitors and printers, vector data and software continue to be widely used, especially when a high degree of geometric precision is required, and when complex information can be decomposed into simple geometric primitives.
[src:svg-graphics/vector-graphics] Thus, it is the preferred model for domains such as engineering, architecture, surveying, 3D rendering, and typography, but is entirely inappropriate for applications such as photography and remote sensing, where raster is more effective and efficient.
[src:svg-graphics/vector-graphics] Some application domains, such as geographic information systems (GIS) and graphic design, use both vector and raster graphics at times, depending on purpose.
[src:svg-graphics/vector-graphics] Vector graphics are based on the mathematics of analytic or coordinate geometry, and is not related to other mathematical uses of the term vector.
[src:svg-graphics/vector-graphics] This can lead to some confusion in disciplines in which both meanings are used.
[src:svg-graphics/vector-graphics] The logical data model of vector graphics is based on the mathematics of coordinate geometry, in which shapes are defined as a set of points in a two- or three-dimensional cartesian coordinate system, as *p* = (*x, y*) or *p* = (*x, y, z*).
[src:svg-graphics/vector-graphics] Because almost all shapes consist of an infinite number of points, the vector model defines a limited set of geometric primitives that can be specified using a finite sample of salient points called vertices.
[src:svg-graphics/vector-graphics] For example, a square can be unambiguously defined by the locations of three of its four corners, from which the software can interpolate the connecting boundary lines and the interior space.
[src:svg-graphics/vector-graphics] Because it is a regular shape, a square could also be defined by the location of one corner, a size (width=height), and a rotation angle.
[src:svg-graphics/vector-graphics] In many vector datasets, each shape can be combined with a set of properties.
[src:svg-graphics/vector-graphics] The most common are visual characteristics, such as color, line weight, or dash pattern.
[src:svg-graphics/vector-graphics] In systems in which shapes represent real-world features, such as GIS and BIM, a variety of attributes of each represented feature can be stored, such as name, age, size, and so on.
[src:svg-graphics/vector-graphics] In some Vector data, especially in GIS, information about topological relationships between objects may be represented in the data model, such as tracking the connections between road segments in a transport network.
[src:svg-graphics/vector-graphics] If a dataset stored in one vector file format is converted to another file format that supports all the primitive objects used in that particular image, then the conversion can be lossless.
[src:svg-graphics/vector-graphics] Vector-based devices, such as the vector CRT and the pen plotter, directly control a drawing mechanism to produce geometric shapes.
[src:svg-graphics/vector-graphics] Since vector display devices can define a line by dealing with just two points (that is, the coordinates of each end of the line), the device can reduce the total amount of data it must deal with by organizing the image in terms of pairs of points.
[src:svg-graphics/vector-graphics] Vector graphic displays were first used in 1958 by the US SAGE air defense system.
[src:svg-graphics/vector-graphics] Vector graphics systems were retired from the U.S. en route air traffic control in 1999.
[src:svg-graphics/vector-graphics] Vector graphics were also used on the TX-2 at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology Lincoln Laboratory by computer graphics pioneer Ivan Sutherland to run his program Sketchpad in 1963.
[src:svg-graphics/vector-graphics] Subsequent vector graphics systems, most of which iterated through dynamically modifiable stored lists of drawing instructions, include the IBM 2250, Imlac PDS-1, and DEC GT40.
[src:svg-graphics/vector-graphics] There was a video game console that used vector graphics called Vectrex as well as various arcade games like *Asteroids*, *Space Wars*, *Tempest* and many cinematronics titles such as *Rip Off*, and *Tail Gunner* using vector monitors.
[src:svg-graphics/vector-graphics] Storage scope displays, such as the Tektronix 4014, could display vector images but not modify them without first erasing the display.
[src:svg-graphics/vector-graphics] However, these were never as widely used as the raster-based scanning displays used for television, and had largely disappeared by the mid-1980s except for specialized applications.
[src:svg-graphics/vector-graphics] Plotters used in technical drawing still draw vectors directly to paper by moving a pen as directed through the two-dimensional space of the paper.
[src:svg-graphics/vector-graphics] However, as with monitors, these have largely been replaced by the wide-format printer that prints a raster image (which may be rendered from vector data).
[src:svg-graphics/vector-graphics] Because this model is useful in a variety of application domains, many different software programs have been created for drawing, manipulating, and visualizing vector graphics.
[src:svg-graphics/vector-graphics] While these are all based on the same basic vector data model, they can interpret and structure shapes very differently, using very different file formats.
[src:svg-graphics/vector-graphics] Vector graphics are commonly found today in the SVG, WMF, EPS, PDF, CDR or AI types of graphic file formats, and are intrinsically different from the more common raster graphics file formats such as JPEG, PNG, APNG, GIF, WebP, BMP and MPEG4.
[src:svg-graphics/vector-graphics] The World Wide Web Consortium (W3C) standard for vector graphics is Scalable Vector Graphics (SVG).
[src:svg-graphics/vector-graphics] The standard is complex and has been relatively slow to be established at least in part owing to commercial interests.
[src:svg-graphics/vector-graphics] Many web browsers now have some support for rendering SVG data but full implementations of the standard are still comparatively rare.
[src:svg-graphics/vector-graphics] In recent years, SVG has become a significant format that is completely independent of the resolution of the rendering device, typically a printer or display monitor.
[src:svg-graphics/vector-graphics] SVG files are essentially printable text that describes both straight and curved paths, as well as other attributes.
[src:svg-graphics/vector-graphics] Wikipedia prefers SVG for images such as simple maps, line illustrations, coats of arms, and flags, which generally are not like photographs or other continuous-tone images.
[src:svg-graphics/vector-graphics] Rendering SVG requires conversion to a raster format at a resolution appropriate for the current task.
[src:svg-graphics/vector-graphics] SVG is also a format for animated graphics.
[src:svg-graphics/vector-graphics] There is also a version of SVG for mobile phones called SVGT (SVG Tiny version).
[src:svg-graphics/vector-graphics] These images can count links and also exploit anti-aliasing.
[src:svg-graphics/vector-graphics] They can also be displayed as wallpaper.
[src:svg-graphics/vector-graphics] CAD software uses its own vector data formats, usually proprietary formats created by software vendors, such as Autodesk's DWG and public exchange formats such as DXF.
[src:svg-graphics/vector-graphics] Modern displays and printers are raster devices; vector formats have to be converted to a raster format (bitmaps – pixel arrays) before they can be rendered (displayed or printed).
[src:svg-graphics/vector-graphics] The size of the bitmap/raster-format file generated by the conversion will depend on the resolution required, but the size of the vector file generating the bitmap/raster file will always remain the same.
[src:svg-graphics/vector-graphics] Thus, it is easy to convert from a vector file to a range of bitmap/raster file formats but it is much more difficult to go in the opposite direction, especially if subsequent editing of the vector picture is required.
[src:svg-graphics/vector-graphics] It might be an advantage to save an image created from a vector source file as a bitmap/raster format, because different systems have different (and incompatible) vector formats, and some might not support vector graphics at all.
[src:svg-graphics/vector-graphics] However, once a file is converted from the vector format, it is likely to be bigger, and it loses the advantage of scalability without loss of resolution.
[src:svg-graphics/vector-graphics] It will also no longer be possible to edit individual parts of the image as discrete objects.
[src:svg-graphics/vector-graphics] The file size of a vector graphic image depends on the number of graphic elements it contains; it is a list of descriptions.
[src:svg-graphics/vector-graphics] Vector art is ideal for printing since the art is made from a series of mathematical curves; it will print very crisply even when resized.
[src:svg-graphics/vector-graphics] For instance, one can print a vector logo on a small sheet of copy paper, and then enlarge the same vector logo to billboard size and keep the same crisp quality.
[src:svg-graphics/vector-graphics] A low-resolution raster graphic would blur or pixelate excessively if it were enlarged from business card size to billboard size.
[src:svg-graphics/vector-graphics] If we regard typographic characters as images, then the same considerations that we have made for graphics apply even to the composition of written text for printing (typesetting).
[src:svg-graphics/vector-graphics] Older character sets were stored as bitmaps.
[src:svg-graphics/vector-graphics] Therefore, to achieve maximum print quality they had to be used at a given resolution only; these font formats are said to be non-scalable.
[src:svg-graphics/vector-graphics] High-quality typography is nowadays based on character drawings (fonts) which are typically stored as vector graphics, and as such are scalable to any size.
[src:svg-graphics/vector-graphics] Examples of these vector formats for characters are Postscript fonts and TrueType fonts.
[src:svg-graphics/vector-graphics] For example, consider a circle of radius *r*.
[src:svg-graphics/vector-graphics] Vector formats are not always appropriate in graphics work and also have numerous disadvantages.
[src:svg-graphics/vector-graphics] For example, devices such as cameras and scanners produce essentially continuous-tone raster graphics that are impractical to convert into vectors, and so for this type of work, an image editor will operate on the pixels rather than on drawing objects defined by mathematical expressions.
[src:svg-graphics/vector-graphics] Comprehensive graphics tools will combine images from vector and raster sources, and may provide editing tools for both, since some parts of an image could come from a camera source, and others could have been drawn using vector tools.
[src:svg-graphics/vector-graphics] Some authors have criticized the term *vector graphics* as being confusing.
[src:svg-graphics/vector-graphics] In particular, *vector graphics* does not simply refer to graphics described by Euclidean vectors.
[src:svg-graphics/vector-graphics] Some authors have proposed to use *object-oriented graphics* instead.
[src:svg-graphics/vector-graphics] However this term can also be confusing as it can be read as any kind of graphics implemented using object-oriented programming.
[src:svg-graphics/vector-graphics] Vector graphics editors typically allow translation, rotation, mirroring, stretching, skewing, affine transformations, changing of z-order (loosely, what's in front of what) and combination of primitives into more complex objects.
[src:svg-graphics/vector-graphics] More sophisticated transformations include set operations on closed shapes (union, difference, intersection, etc.).
[src:svg-graphics/vector-graphics] In SVG, the composition operations are based on alpha composition.
[src:svg-graphics/vector-graphics] Vector graphics are ideal for simple or composite drawings that need to be device-independent, or do not need to achieve photo-realism.
[src:svg-graphics/vector-graphics] For example, the PostScript and PDF page description languages use a vector graphics model.
[src:svg-graphics/vector-graphics] Many stock photo websites provide vectorized versions of hosted images, while specific repositories specialize in vector images given their growing popularity among graphic designers.
[src:svg-graphics/web-svg] As such, it's a text-based, open Web standard for describing images that can be rendered cleanly at any size and are designed specifically to work well with other web standards including CSS, DOM, JavaScript, and SMIL.
[src:svg-graphics/web-svg] SVG is, essentially, to graphics what HTML is to text.
[src:svg-graphics/web-svg] SVG images and their related behaviors are defined in XML text files, which means they can be searched, indexed, scripted, and compressed.
[src:svg-graphics/web-svg] Additionally, this means they can be created and edited with any text editor or with drawing software.
[src:svg-graphics/web-svg] Compared to classic bitmapped image formats such as JPEG or PNG, SVG-format vector images can be rendered at any size without loss of quality and can be easily localized by updating the text within them, without the need of a graphical editor to do so.
[src:svg-graphics/web-svg] With proper libraries, SVG files can even be localized on-the-fly.
[src:svg-graphics/web-svg] SVG has been developed by the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C) since 1999.
[src:svg-graphics/web-svg] The SVG tutorials are designed to walk you through subjects assuming that you have no prior experience, starting from the basics and progressing to more advanced techniques.
[src:svg-graphics/web-svg] This tutorial aims to explain the internals of SVG and is packed with technical details.
[src:svg-graphics/web-svg] If you just want to draw beautiful images, you might find more useful resources at Inkscape's documentation page.
[src:svg-graphics/web-svg] Another good introduction to SVG is provided by the W3C's SVG Primer.
[src:svg-graphics/web-svg] Also check out this advent calendar-themed SVG Tutorial that walks you through coding 25 festive SVGs.
[src:svg-graphics/web-svg] The SVG guides help you work with SVG on the web, covering topics such as embedding, MIME (media) types, handling scripts, animations, filters, and more.
[src:svg-graphics/web-svg] Modern browsers support using SVG within CSS styles to apply graphical effects to HTML content.
[src:svg-graphics/web-svg] SVG makes use of a number of data types.
[src:svg-graphics/web-svg] This article lists these types along with their syntax and descriptions of what they're used for.
[src:svg-graphics/web-svg] Namespaces are essential to user agents that support multiple XML dialects.
[src:svg-graphics/web-svg] Browsers must be very strict; taking the time to understand namespaces now will save you from future headaches.
[src:svg-graphics/web-svg] There are several ways to create and manipulate SVG using JavaScript.
[src:svg-graphics/web-svg] This document describes event handling, interactivity and working with embedded SVG content.
[src:svg-graphics/web-svg] SMIL is an XML-based language for writing interactive multimedia presentations.
[src:svg-graphics/web-svg] Authors can use SMIL syntax in SVG to define the timing and layout of elements for animation.
[src:svg-graphics/web-svg] SVG can be used as an image format in HTML, CSS, certain SVG elements, and via the Canvas API.
[src:svg-graphics/web-svg] This page lists the features where you can provide SVG as an image source.
[src:svg-graphics/web-svg] SVG supports filters so authors can apply effects such as a shadow or blur, or even merge the results of different filters.
[src:svg-graphics/web-svg] This article shows how to use inline SVG and includes examples for illustration.
[src:svg-graphics/web-svg] The SVG reference documentation contains comprehensive information about elements, attributes, and DOM interfaces, and lists relevant specifications and standards documents.
[src:svg-graphics/web-svg] The SVG elements used to construct, draw, and layout vector graphics.
[src:svg-graphics/web-svg] The SVG attributes available that can be used to specify how an element should be handled or rendered.
[src:svg-graphics/web-svg] The SVG DOM API for interacting with SVG using JavaScript.
